[[File:Kuriyasawa, Sukagawa, Fukushima Prefecture 962-0866, Japan - panoramio.jpg|thumb|280px|Taimatsu Akashi]] '''Taimatsu Akashi''' (松明あかし) is a {{ill|fire festival|ja|火祭り|qq=draft|qq=draft}} held in {{ill|Sukagawa, Fukushima|ja|須賀川市|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, {{ill|Fukushima Prefecture|ja|福島県|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, with a history spanning over 430 years. It is sometimes counted among {{ill|Japan's Three Great Fire Festivals|ja|日本三大火祭り|qq=draft|qq=draft}}. The festival takes place annually on the second Saturday of {{ill|November|ja|11月|qq=draft|qq=draft}}.
== Overview == The festival is organized by the Sukagawa City Chamber of Commerce and features large {{ill|torches|ja|松明|qq=draft|qq=draft}} lit as a prayer for protection against disasters and a memorial for those who perished in historical battles.
== History == * In {{ill|1589|ja|1589th year|qq=draft|qq=draft}} ({{ill|Tenshō 17|ja|天正17th year|qq=draft|qq=draft}}), {{ill|Date Masamune|ja|伊達政宗|qq=draft|qq=draft}} expanded his influence into the {{ill|Iwase District|ja|岩瀬郡|qq=draft|qq=draft}} region and demanded the surrender of the {{ill|Nikaidō clan|ja|二階堂氏|qq=draft|qq=draft}} at {{ill|Sukagawa Castle|ja|須賀川城|qq=draft|qq=draft}}. Enraged by this, the retainers and residents gathered on October 10th with torches in hand at {{ill|Tokayama|ja|十日山|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, east of the town, pledging to defend the castle at all costs. This event is considered the origin of the festival. * After the fall of Sukagawa Castle, the festival evolved into a ceremony to console the spirits of those who died in battle. Under new feudal rule, the festival was disguised as a "Mujina Hunt" to avoid interference from the rulers.<ref>[http://www.city.sukagawa.fukushima.jp/2727.htm Sukagawa Tourism Association - Origin of Taimatsu Akashi]</ref> * The festival was historically held on October 10th of the lunar calendar and later shifted to November 10th of the solar calendar. Since {{ill|1986|ja|1986年|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, it has been held on the second Saturday of November. * The sacred fire is taken from {{ill|Nikaido Shrine|ja|二階堂神社|qq=draft|qq=draft}} and carried through Sukagawa City to the event site at {{ill|Midori-gaoka Park|ja|翠ヶ丘公園|qq=draft|qq=draft}}. * In {{ill|1995|ja|1995th year|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, the festival was held a month earlier on October 14th to coincide with the "Fukushima Kokutai" event. * In {{ill|2011|ja|2011th year|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, due to the effects of the {{ill|Fukushima nuclear accident|ja|福島第一原子力発電所事故|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, local {{ill|Torreya nucifera|lt=kaya grass|ja|カヤ|qq=draft|qq=draft}} used for the torches was found to contain trace amounts of radioactive material. Materials were sourced from across Japan to continue the festival.<ref>[http://www.asahi.com/national/update/1112/TKY201111120409.html 'Fukushima's Sukagawa Hosts Taimatsu Akashi with Nationwide Material Support'] (Asahi.com, November 12, 2011)</ref><ref>[http://www.yomiuri.co.jp/national/news/20111113-OYT1T00264.htm 'Flames of Recovery Brighten Fukushima - Taimatsu Akashi Held'] (Yomiuri Online, November 13, 2011)</ref> * The {{ill|2020|ja|2020th year|qq=draft|qq=draft}} and {{ill|2021|ja|2021st year|qq=draft|qq=draft}} festivals were held without spectators to prevent the spread of COVID-19.
== Access == * Sukagawa City is about 1 hour from {{ill|Tokyo|ja|東京|qq=draft|qq=draft}} via the {{ill|Tōhoku Shinkansen|ja|東北新幹線|qq=draft|qq=draft}} (transfer at {{ill|Koriyama Station (Fukushima)|ja|郡山駅|qq=draft|qq=draft}}), and approximately 1 hour 40 minutes from {{ill|Sendai|ja|仙台|qq=draft|qq=draft}} or {{ill|Utsunomiya|ja|宇都宮市|qq=draft|qq=draft}}. * 15-minute walk from {{ill|Sukagawa Station|ja|須賀川駅|qq=draft|qq=draft}} (JR Line). * 5-minute drive from {{ill|Sukagawa Interchange|ja|須賀川インターチェンジ|qq=draft|qq=draft}} on the {{ill|Tōhoku Expressway|ja|東北自動車道|qq=draft|qq=draft}}. * Approximately 2,000 parking spaces are available near the venue.
== References ==
{{Reflist}} == See Also == * {{ill|Fire festival|ja|火祭り|qq=draft|qq=draft}} * {{ill|Sukagawa, Fukushima|ja|福島県須賀川市|qq=draft|qq=draft}} * {{ill|Japan's Three Great Fire Festivals|ja|日本三大火祭り|qq=draft|qq=draft}}
