[[File:Kuriyasawa, Sukagawa, Fukushima Prefecture 962-0866, Japan - panoramio.jpg|thumb|280px|Taimatsu Akashi]] '''Taimatsu Akashi''' (松明あかし) is a [[:en:Festival of fire|Fire festival]] held in [[:en:Sukagawa, Fukushima|Sukagawa, Fukushima]], [[:en:Fukushima Prefecture|Fukushima Prefecture]], with a history spanning over 430 years. It is sometimes counted among {{ill|Japan's Three Great Fire Festivals|ja|日本三大火祭り|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Japan's Three Great Fire Festivals|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid}}. The festival takes place annually on the second Saturday of [[:en:November|November]].
== Overview == The festival is organized by the Sukagawa City Chamber of Commerce and features large {{ill|torches|ja|松明|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/torches|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to たいまつ}} lit as a prayer for protection against disasters and a memorial for those who perished in historical battles.
== History == * In [[:en:1589|1589]] ({{ill|Tenshō 17|ja|天正17年|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tenshō 17|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid}}), [[:en:Date Masamune|Date Masamune]] expanded his influence into the [[:en:Iwase District, Fukushima|Iwase District]] region and demanded the surrender of the [[:en:Nikaidō clan|Nikaidō clan]] at {{ill|Sukagawa Castle|ja|須賀川城|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Sukagawa Castle|qq=}}. Enraged by this, the retainers and residents gathered on October 10th with torches in hand at {{ill|Tokayama|ja|十日山|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tokayama|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid}}, east of the town, pledging to defend the castle at all costs. This event is considered the origin of the festival. * After the fall of Sukagawa Castle, the festival evolved into a ceremony to console the spirits of those who died in battle. Under new feudal rule, the festival was disguised as a "Mujina Hunt" to avoid interference from the rulers.<ref>[http://www.city.sukagawa.fukushima.jp/2727.htm Sukagawa Tourism Association - Origin of Taimatsu Akashi]</ref> * The festival was historically held on October 10th of the lunar calendar and later shifted to November 10th of the solar calendar. Since [[:en:1986|1986]], it has been held on the second Saturday of November. * The sacred fire is taken from {{ill|Nikaido Shrine|ja|二階堂神社|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Nikaido Shrine|qq=}} and carried through Sukagawa City to the event site at {{ill|Midori-gaoka Park|ja|翠ヶ丘公園|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Midori-gaoka Park|qq=}}. * In [[:en:1995|1995]], the festival was held a month earlier on October 14th to coincide with the "Fukushima Kokutai" event. * In [[:en:2011|2011]], due to the effects of the [[:en:Fukushima nuclear accident|Fukushima nuclear accident]], local [[:en:Torreya nucifera|kaya grass]] used for the torches was found to contain trace amounts of radioactive material. Materials were sourced from across Japan to continue the festival.<ref>[http://www.asahi.com/national/update/1112/TKY201111120409.html 'Fukushima's Sukagawa Hosts Taimatsu Akashi with Nationwide Material Support'] (Asahi.com, November 12, 2011)</ref><ref>[http://www.yomiuri.co.jp/national/news/20111113-OYT1T00264.htm 'Flames of Recovery Brighten Fukushima - Taimatsu Akashi Held'] (Yomiuri Online, November 13, 2011)</ref> * The [[:en:2020|2020]] and [[:en:2021|2021]] festivals were held without spectators to prevent the spread of COVID-19.
== Access == * Sukagawa City is about 1 hour from {{ill|Tokyo|ja|東京|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tokyo|qq=}} via the [[:en:Tōhoku Shinkansen|Tōhoku Shinkansen]] (transfer at [[:en:Kōriyama Station|Koriyama Station (Fukushima)]]), and approximately 1 hour 40 minutes from {{ill|Sendai|ja|仙台|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Sendai|qq=}} or [[:en:Utsunomiya|Utsunomiya]]. * 15-minute walk from [[:en:Sukagawa Station|Sukagawa Station]] (JR Line). * 5-minute drive from {{ill|Sukagawa Interchange|ja|須賀川インターチェンジ|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Sukagawa Interchange|qq=}} on the [[:en:Tōhoku Expressway|Tōhoku Expressway]]. * Approximately 2,000 parking spaces are available near the venue.
